 , with which there may well have been some interchange.","Irish (Clare and Cork): from variant of   Mullen  .","English: there has been some confusion with   Mullings  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Mullens","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Mullins  .","Flemish and Dutch: topographic name for someone who lived at a mill or, by extension, an occupational name for a miller."]},{"name":"Molin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Lars, Gunard, Jarl, Nils.  French Moliere, Pascale, Victoire.","Swedish: ornamental or topographic name from <i>mo</i> ‘sandy heath’ + the suffix <i>-lin</i>, derived from Latin <i>-(l)inius</i> ‘relating to’, or from the root of Latin <i>molinarius</i> ‘miller’ or <i>mola</i> ‘mill’ + the suffix <i>-in</i>, derived from Latin <i>-inius</i> ‘relating to’.","Italian (Veneto): variant of   Molino  ."]}]},{"name":"Priscilla","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of New Testament origin: from a post-classical Latin personal name, a feminine diminutive of the Roman family name <i>Priscus</i> ‘ancient’. <i>Priscilla</i> was the name of a woman with whom  St Paul  stayed at Corinth (Acts 18:3), referred to elsewhere as <i>Prisca</i>. The name was in regular use in the late 16th century and enjoyed a modest vogue in the 19th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Priscilla Mullins was born in 1457, in Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 daughter with Sir William Bass. She died after 1482, in her hometown."},"et":{"1457–after 1482":"1457–pärast 1482","1455–1482":"1455–1482","1480–1540":"1480–1540","1457–1482":"1457–1482","1457":"1457","1455":"1455","1540":"1540","after 1482":"pärast 1482","1482":"1482","1480":"1480","Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Hertfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Scroby, Hertfordshire, England":"Hertfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Scrooby, Nottinghamshire, England":"Scrooby